[!INFO] Diagnostic criteria for LADA

  • Age greater than 35 years.
  • Positive autoantibodies to islet beta cells.
  • Insulin INdependence for at least the initial 6 months after initial diagnosis.

Video

Lung metastasis and appearances

  • Pulmonary metastases normally appear peripherally as rounded nodules of differing sizes seen across both lungs. Abnormal features consist of calcification, haemorrhage, consolidation, cavitation and pneumothorax.
  • Cavitation -> squamous cell carcinoma.
  • Calcification -> osteosarcomas and chondrosarcomas, metastases from papillary thyroid carcinoma.
  • Adenocarcinoma metastases spread along the walls of alveoli, instead of destroying the lung parenchyma, resulting in consolidation like that seen with pneumonia.
  • Haemorrhagic pulmonary metastases -> choriocarcinoma and angiosarcoma. (mnemonic: placenta is vascular, angiosarcoma has angio in the name)
  • A miliary pattern of metastases is visualised with renal cell carcinoma and malignant melanoma. (m for melaona, renal -> canon ball metz in uniform distribution)

Advanced life support (ALS / Resuscitation)

- Non shockable rhythm: ***Adrenaline 1mg ASAP*.** **(10ml of 1:10,000 IV or 1ml of 1:1000 IV)** 
    - **NOTE: Adrenaline 1 in 1000 refers to 1mg / mL**
- Shockable rhythm: Adrenaline 1mg IV **AFTER THE 3RD SHOCK** (??adrenaline is delayed until 3rd shock due to arrhtyhmogenicity?)
